land, Verenigd Koninkrijk","East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England":"East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"en":{"1391–after 1430":"1391–after 1430","1391–1430":"1391–1430","1425–1492":"1425–1492","1425":"1425","1430":"1430","1492":"1492","after 1430":"after 1430","1391":"1391","Chevet, Yorkshire, England":"Chevet, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom","East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England":"East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England","England":"England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Amias","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from the French city of Amiens (Somme), which is recorded as  <i>Samarobriva Ambianorum</i> in classical sources.  <i>Samarobriva</i> is a Celtic place-name meaning ‘the bridge over the river Somme’, while the affix  <i>Ambianorum</i> means ‘of the Ambiani’.  <i>Ambiāni</i> is an ethnic name deriving from Celtic  <i>ambi(o)-</i> ‘around’, probably meaning ‘those on both sides (of the Somme)’ or possibly ‘the people of the world’. The affix has replaced the place-name which it once qualified, and it is the ablative form  <i>Ambiānis</i> of this ethnic name which is the source of the current place-name Amiens. For the development of the surname in England, compare ‘merchants of  <i>Amias</i>’, 1326 in   London Letter Books   E (London)."],"variants":[{"name":"Ames","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): from the Old French personal name <i>Amis</i> or from the feminine form, <i>Amice</i>. The Old French word <i>amis</i>, is from Latin <i>amicus</i> ‘friend’, which was used in Late Latin as a term for a man of the lower classes, in particular a slave. There were also derivatives of this as personal names, in particular masculine <i>Amicius</i> and feminine <i>Amicia</i>. Both were in use as personal names in England and may have contributed to the surname.","German: perhaps a nickname for an active person, from an ancient Germanic word related to Old High German <i>amazzig</i> ‘busy’.","Dutch: possibly a patronymic from <i>Ame</i> a common personal name in Holland and Friesland, an abbreviated form of an ancient Germanic personal name, perhaps beginning with <i>amel</i> ‘strong’."]},{"name":"London Letter Books","meanings":["English: (i) occupational name, nickname from Middle English, Anglo-Norman French  <i>bourdour</i>,  <i>bordere</i> ‘jester, joker, buffoon’. (ii) status name from Middle English  <i>border(e)</i> ‘bordar, cottager’ (Old French  <i>bordier</i>, Latin  <i>bordarius</i>), a feudal tenant of the lowest rank. (iii) occupational name perhaps, as Reaney suggests, from an unrecorded Middle English * <i>border</i> ‘maker of boards or tables’. Compare Robert Bordmakere, 1356 in   London Letter Books   G; William  <i>le Bordhewere</i>, 1327 in   Fransson  ; Richard Bordwreghte, 1332 in   Subsidy Rolls   (Sussex)."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament: ‘God is gracious’.  See  <b>John</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Amias Sir, Amias of Chevet was born in 1391, in East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England. He had at least 1 son with Lady Elizabeth Anne Southill. He died after 1430, in England."},"et":{"1391–after 1430":"1391–pärast 1430","1391–1430":"1391–1430","1425–1492":"1425–1492","1425":"1425","1430":"1430","1492":"1492","after 1430":"pärast 1430","1391":"1391","Chevet, Yorkshire, England":"Chevet, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England":"East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England","England":"England"},"fi":{"1391–after 1430":"1391–1430 jälkeen","1391–1430":"1391–1430","1425–1492":"1425–1492","1425":"1425","1430":"1430","1492":"1492","after 1430":"1430 jälkeen","1391":"1391","Chevet, Yorkshire, England":"Chevet, Yorkshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England":"East Ardsley, Yorkshire, England","Englan